<p>President Emmanuel Macron reappointed Sébastien Lecornu as France’s prime minister four days after his resignation, tasking him to form a government and steer a slimmed‑down 2026 budget through a hung parliament [reuters.com#1][newarab.com#1][nytimes.com#2]. Lecornu, 39, said he would build a “government of mission” not “imprisoned by the parties” and pledged to work with all mainstream political movements to reflect parliamentary reality [thehindu.com#1][france24.com#2]. He faces a tight timetable, with a requirement to present the budget bill by Monday and pressure to assemble a cabinet by Sunday evening [france24.com#5][france24.com#4][michaelwest.com.au#1]. The move drew sharp opposition reactions — including vows to bring down the new cabinet — even as Lecornu’s humble post‑resignment</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/REkCCd0RCZ1SuCUv6nMfwfZTG-GjQNavW_f2tVSeUbgGb2vyqeJASR6UlaLsGau-CQ5olO5cbT6RZdUU8wpBC22Owgpt-jjuWWqXnuv5hFkVRMhpe_IcmLuF5bNc1xD9jXz9mR-yEqtQWLT_y5lcGbSKq1tBaBkqMO3GISYkzzEkhpksg5itoXbS98XNHZb_RG-y49UbQL4UVwTolz3zi0OApqXNemkd' alt='Emmanuel Macron reappoints Sébastien Lecornu as prime minister of France.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Budget deadlines: Lecornu must present the 2026 budget bill by Monday, with state and social security budgets needing to be in place by December 31 [france24.com#4][michaelwest.com.au#1].</li><li>Opposition stance: Far-right leader Jordan Bardella called the reappointment a &quot;bad joke&quot; and vowed to immediately seek to vote out the new cabinet [nytimes.com#1][newarab.com#1].</li><li>Cabinet approach: Lecornu insists the new cabinet must not be &quot;hostage&quot; to partisan interests and should be free of 2027 presidential ambitions [france24.com#3][france24.com#2][thehindu.com#1].</li><li>Popularity shift: His popularity rose after a post‑resignation TV appearance, with many praising his humble tone [reuters.com#1][straitstimes.com#1].</li><li>Political backdrop: France has faced months of deadlock since last year’s snap polls produced a hung parliament and more seats for the far-right [newarab.com#1][nytimes.com#2].</li></ul><blockquote>I don&#x27;t have an agenda. I have no other ambition than to get through this moment, which is objectively very difficult for everyone. - Sebastien Lecornu</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Élysée Palace: Announced Lecornu’s reappointment and tasked him with forming a government. (<a href='https://www.newarab.com/news/macron-reappoints-lecornu-frances-pm-days-after-he-quit'>The New Arab</a>)</li><li>Sébastien Lecornu: Said he accepted out of duty and aims to end the political crisis with a budget by year-end. (<a href='https://www.newarab.com/news/macron-reappoints-lecornu-frances-pm-days-after-he-quit'>The New Arab</a>)</li><li>National Rally (Jordan Bardella): Called the pick a “bad joke” and pledged to try to oust the government. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2025/10/11/world/europe/france-macron-lecornu-prime-minister.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li><li>Socialist Party: Said there is no deal with Lecornu and demanded suspension of the 2023 pensions reform as a condition. (<a href='https://www.newarab.com/news/macron-reappoints-lecornu-frances-pm-days-after-he-quit'>The New Arab</a>)</li><li>Sébastien Lecornu (on cabinet makeup): Wants a government not imprisoned by parties and free from 2027 ambitions, reflecting parliamentary reality. (<a href='https://www.france24.com/en/video/20251011-returning-pm-lecornu-says-wants-govt-free-from-party-jockeying'>FRANCE 24</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.lemonde.fr/en/politics/article/2025/10/11/macron-keeps-lecornu-on-as-prime-minister-despite-political-parties-hostility_6746323_5.html'>Macron keeps Lecornu on as prime minister despite political parties&#x27; hostility</a> - lemonde.fr</li><li><a href='https://www.thehindu.com/news/international/french-pm-lecornu-says-new-government-must-reflect-parliamentary-reality/article70151923.ece'